ddhist meditation, Sufi contemplation, Eastern Orthodox prayer, Pure Land Buddhist visualization, Hindu classical Yoga, Dominican Catholic prayer, Daoist internal alchemy, and modern therapeutic meditation. Each introduction to a contemplative text discusses its historical context, the associated religious tradition and literature, the method of contemplative practice, and the text's legacy and influence. Volume editor Louis Komjathy opens the work with a thoughtful consideration of interpretive issues in the emerging interdisciplinary field of contemplative studies. Readers will gain not only a nuanced understanding of important works of contemplative literature, but also resources for understanding contemplative practice and contemplative experience from a comparative and cross-cultural perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aContemplation. 0aMeditation. 0aReligions. 4aPhilosophy : Contemplative Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aBirkel, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, Edwin F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuehler, Arthur F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Constance A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomjathy, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomjathy, Louis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMagid, Shaul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGuckin, John Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhilibert, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, Harold D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re